[[File:WLV-604.JPG|thumb|Lanby buoy (on left) that replaced [[Lightship Columbia]] at the [[Columbia River Maritime Museum]] in Oregon]] '''Lanby buoy''' is a contraction of Large Automatic Navigation BuoY.<ref name=cil>{{cite web |publisher=Commissioners of Irish Lights |title=Abbreviations |url=http://www.cil.ie/sh903x5291.html |accessdate=2008-06-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119030619/http://www.cil.ie/sh903x5291.html |archivedate=2007-11-19 |df= }}</ref> Lanby buoys were first made in the USA by [[General Dynamics]] and adapted by [[Hawker Siddeley Dynamics]] for use in British waters in the early 1970s.<ref name=vads>{{cite web |publisher=Visual Arts Data Service |title=Design 1970 Journal - Things seen (Desert Island discus) |url=http://vads.ahds.ac.uk/diad/article.php?year=1970&title=254&article=d.254.32 |accessdate=2015-07-06|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717164917/http://vads.ahds.ac.uk/diad/article.php?year=1970&title=254&article=d.254.32|archivedate=2011-07-17}}</ref> The buoys were intended to replace [[Lightvessel|lightships]] and were constructed as a circular hull with a central light to provide all-round visibility and a foghorn. They may also contain radio and radio beacons. The navigation buoy was to be monitored remotely from onshore and was designed to run for extended periods without repair. The running costs were estimated to be as little as 10% of those of a lightship.<ref name=vads />
However, experience showed that it was difficult to attain the required reliability in British waters due to the high acceleration forces experienced in rough seas with 14m waves and 7 knot currents. Alternative experiments were made with platforms such as the [[Royal Sovereign Lighthouse]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rowlands|first=David|title=Points of Reference|year=1974|journal=Design Journal|volume=310|pages=48-53|url=http://vads.ac.uk/diad/article.php?title=310&year=1974&article=d.310.39|ref=harv|accessdate=Jul 6, 2015}}</ref> The automatic technology was later used successfully in more conventional lightships.
A Lanby buoy replaced the Bar Lightship PLANET in the [[River Mersey|Mersey]] [[estuary]] in 1972 and remained in service for 21 years before being replaced itself.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Mersey Lightvessel Preservation Society |title=History of the Mersey Lightvessels |url=http://www.barlightvessel.org.uk/history.html |accessdate=2008-06-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422002057/http://www.barlightvessel.org.uk/history.html |archivedate=2008-04-22 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
